User Guide: ESP32 Telescope Collimator
This guide covers the setup, usage, and troubleshooting for your digital collimation tool.
1. Initial Setup
The firmware is configured specifically for AI-Thinker ESP32-CAM boards.
Requirements:
● Board: AI-Thinker ESP32-CAM (or clone like DORHEA)
● Power: 5V Micro-USB (High Quality)
● Settings in Arduino IDE:
○ Board: "AI Thinker ESP32-CAM"
○ PSRAM: "Enabled" (Crucial!)
○ Partition Scheme: "Huge APP (3MB No OTA)"
Flashing:
1. Connect GPIO 0 to GND.
2. Press Reset.
3. Upload the code provided above.4. Remove the GPIO 0 wire and press Reset again.
2. Connecting to the Tool
This device operates as a Standalone Hotspot. It does not require a home router or internet
access.
1. Power On: Plug the device into a USB battery bank or port.
2. Find Wi-Fi: On your phone, tablet, or laptop, search for the Wi-Fi network:
○ SSID: ESP32_Collimator
○ Password: (None / Open)
3. Open Interface: Open your web browser and navigate to:
○ http://192.168.4.1 (or http://collimator.local on some Apple devices).
3. Using the Collimator
The interface is designed for real-time adjustments while looking at your phone screen.
The Display:
● Video Feed: Live, hardware-accelerated B&W video stream (320x240 @ ~25FPS).
● Crosshair (White): Indicates the geometric center of the sensor.
● Circles (Green): Two concentric circles to help align your primary and secondary
mirrors.
The Controls:
● Zoom: Uses digital scaling (CSS) to zoom into the video feed without losing the overlay
alignment. Useful for fine-tuning.
● Position (Center Offset): Moves the Crosshair and Circles together. Use this if your
camera isn't perfectly centered in the 3D-printed case.
○ Rst Button: Instantly resets the position to (0,0).
● Inner Circle: Adjusts the radius of the solid green circle. Align this with your secondary
mirror or donut.
● Outer Circle: Adjusts the radius of the dashed green circle. Align this with your primary
mirror clips or focuser drawtube.
Auto-Save:
● Any adjustment you make (Circle Size or Position) is automatically saved to the ESP32's
flash memory. When you power it on next time, your settings will be exactly where you left
them.
